<TITLE> Seminar urges govt to shun loans </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 14 (bdnews24.com)  NGO activists spoke out against the role of foreign lending agencies and development partners one day before their key meeting with the government. Speakers said at a discussion on Monday that the Bangladesh Development Forum was merely a means to further the hold of foreign lending agencies on the government. They said this was mainly done through innumerable conditions that multilateral agencies like the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, supported by the development partners, impose on Bangladesh. Pointing out that such conditions actually encroach upon the national policy sovereignty by imposing restrictions on the government, the speakers demanded that the government should reject all foreign loans pegged with conditions. Criticising the secretive manner of holding this meeting, speakers said that sessions were not open to the civil society members, non-governmental organisations or the media. The seminar was organised by Voice, a non-governmental organisation. Ahmed Swapan Mahmud, executive director of the NGO, said loans and credit from the international financial institutions only made the people more indebted. Arup Rahee, an activist opposed to the unbridled free market and corporate globalisation, urged the government to formulate its own economic policies instead of accepting those of the foreign agen
